    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i was reading about hiit workouts and it mentioned lactic acid. can u explain how it actually gets made in the muscles when u go hard and how the body gets rid of it afterwards?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Sure, when you go hard during a High-Intensity Interval Training (HIIT) workout, your muscles are working at a high intensity, and they produce lactic acid as a byproduct of anaerobic respiration. This is when your muscles are using energy without enough oxygen, and the lactic acid is like a little sidekick that helps provide energy quickly, but it can also cause a burning sensation in your muscles.\n\nNow, when you're done with your workout, your body doesn't just let that lactic acid hang around. It gets rid of it through a process called lactate shuttle. Think of it like a little train that takes the lactic acid from your muscles and transports it to your liver, where it gets converted back into glucose, which your body can use for energy. It's like the lactic acid is being recycled, so your body can keep going strong. So, even though the lactic acid might make you feel like you're being attacked by a horde of goblins during your workout, your body has a clever way of dealing with it afterwards.",
      "source": "target",
